c]]\n| clubs10             =  [[Hyde United]]\n| caps1               = 0\n| caps2               = 10\n| caps3               = 5\n| caps4               = 37\n| caps5               = 4\n| caps6               = 33\n| caps7               = 58\n| caps8               = 46\n| caps9               = 31\n| caps10              = 36\n| goals1              = 0\n| goals2              = 5\n| goals3              = 1\n| goals4              = 21\n| goals5              = 1\n| goals6              = 18\n| goals7              = 32\n| goals8              = 17\n| goals9              = 11\n| goals10             = 18\n| nationalyears1      = \n| nationalteam1       = \n| nationalcaps1       = \n| nationalgoals1      = \n| club-update         = 17:16, 2 August 2008 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''David Patrick Brown''' (born 29 May 1989) is an English [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]]. He came through the [[Leeds United]] Academy, before moving to [[Nottingham Forest]]. He scored on his [[Football League]] debut for [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]]. Throughout his career he has won 3 promotions and has claimed Player of the year on one occasion in 2015.\n\n==Career==\nBrown was born in [[York]], North Yorkshire,<ref name=\"Hugman 2008-09\"/> and spent ten years in [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]'s youth set up before he moved to [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] at the start of the [[2007-08 in English football|2007\u201308]] season.<ref name=\"trial\">{{cite news\n|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/2013141.Brown_joy_at_teaming_up_with_boyhood_hero/\n|title=Brown joy at teaming up with boyhood hero\n|date=1 February 2008\n|accessdate=13 September 2012\n|newspaper=Telegraph & Argus\n|location=Bradford\n|first=Simon\n|last=Parker}}</ref> In November 2007, he joined [[Eastwood Town F.C.|Eastwood Town]] on an initial one-month loan, which was later extended for a second month.<ref>{{cite news\n |url        = http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/displayNode.jsp?nodeId=136006&command=displayContent&sourceNode=136005&contentPK=19187789&folderPk=78464&pNodeId=136011&bustcache=\n |title      = Brown extends Eastwood stay\n |date       = 7 December 2007\n |accessdate = 2 February 2008\n |newspaper  = Nottingham Evening Post\n}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He returned to Forest in January 2008, after scoring five goals in ten games with Eastwood.<ref>{{cite news\n |url        = http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/displayNode.jsp?nodeId=136006&command=displayContent&sourceNode=136005&contentPK=19604175&folderPk=78464&pNodeId=136011\n |title      = Brown returns to resolve future\n |date       = 19 January 2008\n |accessdate = 2 February 2008\n |newspaper  = Nottingham Evening Post\n}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He departed Forest and joined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on deadline day. After scoring twice in a 4\u20134 reserve game with [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and another against [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]],<ref name=\"trial\"/> he was handed a contract until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7218486.stm\n|title=Bradford sign Bullock from Pools\n|date=31 January 2008\n|accessdate=13 September 2012\n|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> He made his debut two days later on 2 February 2008 as a second-half substitute and scored six minutes after he came on to give Bradford a 1\u20130 victory over [[Macclesfield Town F.C.|Macclesfield Town]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_3/7210673.stm\n|title=Macclesfield 0\u20131 Bradford\n|date=2 February 2008\n|accessdate=13 September 2012\n|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 29 April 2008, Brown along with a staggering 13 players out of contract were deemed to be surplus to requirements at Valley Parade and was released by manager [[Stuart McCall]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/2234555.Johnson_one_of_13_axed_by_City/\n|title=Johnson one of 13 axed by City\n|date=29 April 2008\n|accessdate=13 September 2012\n|newspaper=Telegraph & Argus\n|location=Bradford\n|first=Simon\n|last=Parker}}</ref> He played five games for City, all as substitute.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=48680\n|title=David Brown\n|accessdate=3 May 2008\n|publisher=Soccerbase}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his departure, Brown joined [[Conference National]] club [[York City F.C.|York City]] on trial in July 2008,<ref>{{cite news\n |first       = Dave\n |last        = Flett\n |url         = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/yorkcityfc/news/3197703.Brown_stakes_claim_to_be_a_full_time_Minsterman/\n |title       = Brown stakes claim to be a full-time Minsterman\n |date        = 8 July 2008\n |accessdate  = 13 September 2012\n |newspaper   = The Press\n |location    = York\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://archive.is/20130505111047/http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/yorkcityfc/news/3197703.Brown_stakes_claim_to_be_a_full_time_Minsterman/\n |archivedate = 5 May 2013\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> scoring twice in a pre-season friendly game against [[Tadcaster Albion F.C.|Tadcaster Albion]], which York won 6\u20130.<ref name=\"tadcaster\">{{cite news\n |url        = http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/yorkcityfc/news/3199036.City_boss_weighs_up_final_signing_to_bolster_squad/\n |archive-url = https://archive.is/20130505100528/http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/sport/yorkcityfc/news/3199036.City_boss_weighs_up_final_signing_to_bolster_squad/\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = 5 May 2013\n |title      = City boss weighs up final signing to bolster squad\n |date       = 9 July 2008\n |accessdate = 13 September 2012\n |first      = Dave\n |last       = Flett\n |newspaper  = The Press\n |location   = York\n}}</ref> However, York manager [[Colin Walker (footballer born 1958)|Colin Walker]] said Brown and two other trialists were only making up the numbers and were unlikely to be signed permanently.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7499675.stm\n|title=York squad is complete \u2013 Walker\n|date=10 July 2008\n|accessdate=13 September 2012\n|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> Later the same month, he was given a trial at [[Northern Premier League Premier Division]] side [[Guiseley A.F.C.|Guiseley]], coming on as a second-half substitute in a 2\u20131 pre-season friendly victory over former side Bradford City.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/sportbcfc/sportbcfcmatch/3223044.Evans_gets_second_chance/\n|title=Evans gets second chance\n|date=22 July 2008\n|accessdate=13 September 2012\n|newspaper=Telegraph & Argus\n|location=Bradford\n|first=Simon\n|last=Parker}}</ref> After scoring 2 goals in another pre-season game against a Leeds United XI, he joined Guiseley on a permanent basis.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/sport/football/footballguiseey/conference_north_2011_2012/news_articles/3563337.Guiseley_have_plenty_of_options_up_front_/\n|title=Guiseley have plenty of options up front\n|date=1 August 2008\n|accessdate=13 September 2012\n|newspaper=Telegraph & Argus\n|location=Bradford\n|first=Ian\n|last=Whiting}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, he joined [[Northern Premier League Division One North]] side [[F.C. Halifax Town|Halifax Town]] along with fellow Bradford City player [[Paul Evans (footballer born 1974)|Paul Evans]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/halifaxtown/Wakefield-v-FC-Halifax-Town.4930951.jp\n|title=Wakefield v FC Halifax Town: Two in, one out at the Shay\n|date=30 January 2009\n|accessdate=30 January 2009\n|newspaper=Halifax Courier}}</ref> Brown's debut was as a substitute one day after signing for Halifax, when he scored the final goal during a 4\u20131 victory against [[Wakefield F.C.|Wakefield]].<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.halifaxcourier.co.uk/local/Wakefield-FC-v-FC-Halifax.4934164.jp\n|title=Wakefield FC v FC Halifax Town: Stott at the double\n|date=31 January 2009\n|accessdate=1 February 2009\n|newspaper=Halifax Courier}}</ref>\n\nBrown finished the season with Halifax, but in June 2009, he returned to [[Conference North]] side [[Eastwood Town F.C.|Eastwood Town]], where he had previously played on loan.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eastwoodadvertiser.co.uk/sport/New-signings-to-bring-youth.5357130.jp |title=New signings to bring youth and experience |date=11 June 2009 |accessdate=28 January 2010 |first=Mark |last=Duffy |newspaper=Eastwood Advertiser}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{Hyde United F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, David}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tadcaster]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Leeds United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Nottingham Forest F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Eastwood Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Guiseley A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:F.C. Halifax Town players]]\n[[Category:Bradford (Park Avenue) A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Tadcaster Albion A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Garforth Town A.F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|others of a similar name|David Brown (disambiguation){{!}}David Brown}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = David Brown\n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| fullname            = David Patrick Brown<ref name=\"Hugman 2008-09\">{{cite book\n | editor-first = Barry J.\n | editor-last = Hugman\n | title = The PFA Footballers' Who's Who 2008\u201309\n | publisher = Mainstream Publishing\n | year = 2008\n | isbn = 978-1-84596-324-8\n | page =